<subSubSection pageId="126" pageNumber="127" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="126" pageNumber="127">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="126" pageNumber="127">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 121" captionStartId="F121" captionText="Figure 121. Distribution of Conostegia extinctoria." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure121" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96479" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">121</figureCitation>
). From southern Costa Rica to Colombia, with a disjunct population in the Cordillera de Vilcabamba in Peru, 700-1350 m in elevation. The inclusion of the Peruvian locality is based on a specimen cited by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="973886" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure121" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96479" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" start="Figure 121" startId="F121">
<paragraph pageId="126" pageNumber="127">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">Figure 121.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia extinctoria" order="Myrtales" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="extinctoria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">Conostegia extinctoria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="126" pageNumber="127">
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia extinctoria" order="Myrtales" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="extinctoria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">Conostegia extinctoria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the smallest flowered species in section 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Australis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">Australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The style of this species is exserted as in other species of section 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="126" pageNumber="127" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Australis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">Australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 120" captionStartId="F120" captionText="Figure 120. Conostegia extinctoria. A Fertile branch B Close up of the flower. Photographs by M. A. Buitrago Aristizabal of specimen vouchered J. M. Posada 308." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure120" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96478" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">120</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
commented on the variation within this species, in particular in the number of floral parts. As in other species in this section, some specimens (e.i. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="127">Callejas et al. 8926</emphasis>
- NY) suggest the calyptra is not cleanly circumscissle and instead ruptures at anthesis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
